   it should be flexible to support various application requirements and
   convenient management of infrastructure. Inspired by software-defined
   networking, which aims to make networks more flexible, the authors
   propose a software-defined IoT architecture for smart urban sensing.
   This architecture decouples urban sensing applications from the physical
   infrastructure. Centralized controllers are designed to manage physical
   devices and provide APIs of data acquisition, transmission, and
   processing services to develop urban sensing applications. With these
   properties, various applications can coexist on the shared
   infrastructure, and each application can request controllers to
   customize its data acquisition, transmission, and processing on-demand
