Volume = {{61}},
Number = {{2}},
Pages = {{197-205}},
Month = {{MAY}},
Abstract = {{Despite the rapid advancements in consumer electronics, the data
   transmitted by sensing devices in a smart home environment are still
   vulnerable to anomalies due to node faults, transmission errors, or
   attacks. This affects the reliability of the received sensed data and
   may lead to the incorrect decision making at both local (i.e., smart
   home) and global (i.e., smart city) levels. This study introduces a
   novel mobile agent-based cross-layer anomaly detection scheme, which
   takes into account stochastic variability in cross-layer data obtained
   from received data packets, and defines fuzzy logic-based soft
   boundaries to characterize behavior of sensor nodes. This cross-layer
   design approach empowers the proposed scheme to detect both node and
   link anomalies, and also effectively transmits mobile agents by
   considering the communication link-state before transmission of the
   mobile agent. The proposed scheme is implemented on a real testbed and a
   modular application software is developed to manage the anomaly
   detection system in the smart home. The experimental results show that
   the proposed scheme detects cross-layer anomalies with high accuracy and
   considerably reduces the energy consumption caused by the mobile agent
   transmission in the poor communication link-state situations(1).}},
